Excellent question. You're asking about one of the key features that makes Electron so powerful for creating custom-looking desktop applications.

**Yes, you can absolutely hide the default title bar and menu.**

This is called creating a **frameless window**. It allows you to take full control over the entire application window and design a completely custom title bar within your React application.

### The "How": Creating a Frameless Window

You would do this by adding a single option to the `BrowserWindow` constructor in your `main.js` file:

```javascript
// in main.js

function createWindow () {
  const win = new BrowserWindow({
    width: 1200,
    height: 800,
    minWidth: 960,
    minHeight: 640,
    title: 'ICDV',
    frame: false, // <-- This is the line you would add
    webPreferences: {
      preload: path.join(__dirname, 'preload.js')
    }
  });
  // ...
}
```

### The Catch: What You Lose

As you correctly guessed, when you set `frame: false`, you lose all the native window controls:
*   The minimize, maximize, and close buttons disappear.
*   The ability to drag the window around with your mouse is gone.

### The Solution: Building Your Own Controls

To solve this, you would need to implement two things:

1.  **Custom Window Controls:** You would add your own minimize, maximize, and close buttons to your `Topbar.js` component. These buttons would use the Electron IPC (Inter-Process Communication) system to tell the main process to control the window.

2.  **Draggable Area:** You would tell Electron which parts of your custom title bar should act like the native title bar for dragging. This is done with a simple CSS property.

Here's a brief overview of how it works:

**1. In your `Topbar.js` (React Component):**
You would add the buttons and a CSS style to make the bar draggable.

```jsx
// In Topbar.js
// Add a style to the main AppBar component
<AppBar sx={{ '-webkit-app-region': 'drag' }}>
  {/* ... your existing Topbar content ... */}

  {/* Add custom window controls at the end */}
  <Box sx={{ marginLeft: 'auto', '-webkit-app-region': 'no-drag' }}>
    <IconButton onClick={() => window.electron.minimizeWindow()}>-</IconButton>
    <IconButton onClick={() => window.electron.maximizeWindow()}>o</IconButton>
    <IconButton onClick={() => window.electron.closeWindow()}>x</IconButton>
  </Box>
</AppBar>
```
*(Note: The `-webkit-app-region: 'no-drag'` on the button container is crucial to make sure the buttons themselves are still clickable).*

**2. In your `preload.js`:**
You would expose the functions that send the commands to the main process.

```javascript
// In preload.js
contextBridge.exposeInMainWorld('electron', {
  // ... your other exposed functions
  minimizeWindow: () => ipcRenderer.send('minimize-window'),
  maximizeWindow: () => ipcRenderer.send('maximize-window'),
  closeWindow: () => ipcRenderer.send('close-window'),
});
```

**3. In your `main.js`:**
You would listen for these commands and control the window.

```javascript
// In main.js
ipcMain.on('minimize-window', () => {
  const win = BrowserWindow.getFocusedWindow();
  if (win) win.minimize();
});

ipcMain.on('maximize-window', () => {
  const win = BrowserWindow.getFocusedWindow();
  if (win) {
    if (win.isMaximized()) {
      win.unmaximize();
    } else {
      win.maximize();
    }
  }
});

ipcMain.on('close-window', () => {
  const win = BrowserWindow.getFocusedWindow();
  if (win) win.close();
});
```

So, to summarize: **Yes, it's a very common and powerful feature.** It requires a bit of work to re-implement the controls, but it gives you complete design freedom.

